> `125-129`: **Replaced SSE with StreamableHTTP while preserving context functionality**
> 
> The implementation correctly replaces the SSE transport with the new StreamableHTTP transport while maintaining the important authorization context functionality via `WithHTTPContextFunc`. This ensures that authentication extraction from HTTP headers continues to work with the new transport.
>
[...]
> The streamable HTTP transport specification is somewhat ambiguous.
> 
> The stdio transport operates over a full-duplex, bi-directional long-lived connection — a straightforward model where both request and response can flow freely. This is the baseline on which the spec is built. The old SSE transport is very straightforward compared the local communication. It omit the client-to-server response channel, which is rarely used, and other things keep the same.
> 
> However, the streamable HTTP transport introduces complexity. When the client sets up an optional long-lived GET connection for listening, the behavior is logically the same to SSE. (For the real transportation, response will transmit through the request http connection. But logically it’s the same). But when that long-lived GET listener is not enabled, things getting wired.
> 
> According to the spec, the request http connection could be upgraded to SSE, and it should be terminated when the corresponding response returned. So the SSE connection persists only for the duration of the response handling. When there's no on-going request, i.e. no real connections, the server notifications (e.g., tool-list-changed) cannot even be sent. Attempting to queue such notifications and send them over a future request connection seems impractical for the client business. While the spec mentions resumability and redelivery, that section is intended for broken or interrupted connections — I don't think it's our scenario.
[...]
> 
> Furthermore, the idea of an “upgradable stream” for a response — which by definition must eventually terminate — is confusing. If the stream is treated as a general-purpose notification pipe, it burdens the server with streams avaiable for unpredictable durations. If not, then the server can only use it for request-scoped updates (e.g., progress updates related to that specific request).
> 
> In my implementation, I treat this pragmatically:
> 
> - If there are notifications sent during request handling (via the context), the server will treating these messages as request-related, and sent though the automatically upgraded SSE stream.
> - For global notifications, clients must explicitly set up a long-lived GET connection. Otherwise it will be ignored.
> 
> I think the TypeScript version implemented it this way too, though I’m not very familiar with TypeScript — I might have misunderstood. I’d appreciate it very much if the reviewers could help verify my understanding of the spec.
> 
> Even though the protocol allows server-to-client requests, I’ve yet to see this used in the wild. I tested Cursor and Claude Desktop in March, neither even supported notifications very well. Although HTTP spec may be confusing, I think, in practice most user only needs the simplest one-shot request-response interactions.
> 
> Anyway, HTTP transport is a highly requested feature, and I’d love to see it supported in the project, in any form, ASAP.

